Editorial
---------

Weekly Platform Trends: SiS' 655 Joins the Dual-DDR Party
But Where's the HT Beef?

The prospect of owning a dual-channel DDR system is an attractive one for
many power users. Intel started this trend with its 850 and 850E chipsets,
whose dual-channel memory controllers have basically owned the
high-performance Pentium 4 market since inception.

There are two main reasons for this: performance and value. Dual-channel
architecture can theoretically double the memory bandwidth of a desktop
platform, and with a 533MHz-bus Pentium 4, memory bandwidth is an integral
part of overall performance. Value is also key, as dual-channel design gives
new life to older and cheaper memory: In the case of Intel's E7205 "Granite
Bay" workstation chipset, dual-channel architecture lets even low-end DDR266
prove more than a match for even PC1066 RDRAM.

In short, the handwriting is on the wall, and the platforms that will carry
us into 2003 will almost certainly include dual-channel memory architecture.
One of the first to emerge is the SiS 655, whose main selling point is the
inclusion of dual-channel DDR333.

This is what many users hoped for from Granite Bay, only to find they must
keep waiting for Intel's Springdale -- SiS has seemingly turned the tables
on the Intel juggernaut, especially considering how aggressively the CPU
giant has been marketing and releasing new chipsets.

On the other hand, the lack of other new features -- and the fact that dual
DDR333 isn't actually necessary to satisfy the 4.2GB/sec bandwidth of a
533MHz-bus Pentium 4 -- raise the question, what's the point? In fact, the
SiS 655 looks a whole lot like merely a SiS 648 with an additional memory
channel ...

Vince Freeman
Hardware Central
(See complete text at
http://www.hardwarecentral.com/hardwarecentral/reports/4608/1/)

